---
/**
 * context-engineering/0003 · Figure 5 — "The RAG pipeline"
 * (Question → Retrieval → Assemble → LLM → Answer, fed by the chunk index).
 * Copied VERBATIM from the source lesson (figure + svg + figcaption incl. footnote
 * <sup>). References the shared arrowhead markers (#arw, #arwM) defined once in
 * Fig1.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 150"
        role="img"
        aria-label="RAG pipeline: question to retrieval to context assembly to LLM to answer, with retrieval pulling from a chunk index."
    >
        <rect x="14" y="56" width="96" height="40" rx="8" fill="#eef2f7" stroke="#1f3a5a"
        ></rect><text
            x="62"
            y="80"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#111110">Question</text
        >
        <rect
            x="142"
            y="56"
            width="104"
            height="40"
            rx="8"
            fill="#f1eef2"
            stroke="#b5179e"
            stroke-width="2"></rect><text
            x="194"
            y="74"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#b5179e">Retrieval</text
        ><text x="194" y="87" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >search the index</text
        >
        <rect x="278" y="56" width="104" height="40" rx="8" fill="#f6eef7" stroke="#b5179e"
        ></rect><text
            x="330"
            y="74"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="9.5"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#111110">Assemble</text
        ><text x="330" y="87" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7.5" fill="#6b675f"
            >pack into window</text
        >
        <rect x="414" y="56" width="96" height="40" rx="8" fill="#f6eef7" stroke="#b5179e"
        ></rect><text
            x="462"
            y="80"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#111110">LLM</text
        >
        <rect x="542" y="56" width="84" height="40" rx="8" fill="#e9f3ec" stroke="#2f5d3a"
        ></rect><text
            x="584"
            y="80"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#2f5d3a">Answer</text
        >
        <line x1="110" y1="76" x2="140" y2="76" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line x1="246" y1="76" x2="276" y2="76" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line x1="382" y1="76" x2="412" y2="76" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <line x1="510" y1="76" x2="540" y2="76" stroke="#6b675f" marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <!-- chunk index feeding retrieval -->
        <rect x="142" y="12" width="104" height="28" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#111110"
        ></rect><text
            x="194"
            y="30"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="8.5"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#111110">Chunk index</text
        >
        <line x1="194" y1="40" x2="194" y2="54" stroke="#b5179e" marker-end="url(#arwM)"></line>
        <text x="320" y="128" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-style="italic" fill="#b5179e"
            >the LLM only ever sees what Retrieval surfaced — everything downstream rides on this
            one step</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        RAG is retrieval wired in front of generation. The model answers from <b
            >the retrieved chunks</b
        > rather than its training weights, which is what lets it cite a source, stay current, and reach
        your private data. The whole answer rides on whether retrieval pulled the right chunk.<sup
            ><a href="#s6" id="r6">6</a></sup
        >
    </figcaption>
</figure>
